title: Grateful Dead Live at Hartford Civic Center on 1988-04-05
lineage: Cassette Master (Nakamichi CR-7A) > Tascam DA-3000 (DSF 1-bit/5.8 MHz) >KORG AudioGate 4 > Samplitude Pro X3 Suite > FLAC/24
description:
Set 1

Hell In A Bucket-> Sugaree, Walkin' Blues, Dire Wolf, It's All Over Now, Bird Song, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Might As Well

Set 2

Iko Iko, Louie Louie, Samson & Delilah, Ship of Fools, Smokestack Lightning-> Jam-> Drums-> Jam-> I Need A Miracle-> Wharf Rat-> Throwing Stones-> Not Fade Away, E: Knockin' On Heaven's Door

reviews.review_text: Don't Get To Excited Highlights: Louie Louie

Best Birdsong Electric Not to pick a fight but give this show a listen the boys really speak to each other.  The Birdsong is outrageous.   The All Over Now is awesome as well. The Louie is probably the worst thing played

Good show/great recording I didn’t like this show at the time though I recognized that the muddy sound may have been a factor.  At Hartford Civic Center, it was all about location location location.  If you were above a certain altitude in the second level (almost a guarantee in my experience), you tended to get a thin sound that never got loud enough.  Then there were other locations that made it seem like the band was sitting in the row in front of you playing an intimate set for you.   When I dream that I’m at a Dead show, it’s usually in this venue.  Note to my subconscious: I’d prefer to relive the Saratogas.   Also, I was perhaps a little muddy myself at this show.  I put probably an ounce of that brown weed you just don’t see anymore into a half a pan of brownies and a friend and I ate it and, you know it is, too much too fast but nothin’ that’s gonna kill you but  you do kind of get more and more sleepy as the night goes on until it’s a bit of a struggle to even stay awake…And then there were never any good recordings of this Hartford run back in the day so I was never able to find out if it was actually a good show or not until Mr. Miller posted this super upgrade.  And yeah, It’s a pretty great show.  

The Hell in A Bucket was the first one that really grabbed me as a set opener.  This is a good example of how they rediscovered their psychedelic properties after being fairly straight ahead for much of 87.  “It” was back as, I think Blair Jackson noted in a Golden Road at the time.  Bucket has that “It” especially during the jam which is liquid and hypnotic.  Sugaree suffers a bit from Jerry’s tough vocals but it’s 180 from the first, cringe-inducing night listening to razor blades scraping a throat.  Walkin’ Blues is unique in that they develop a little jam sparked by the audiences’ spontaneous clapping in time.  A groovy version of this.  Love the way All Over Now starts too.  It seems like long pauses and animated discussions often preceded this one as they often tried to rearrange it on the fly.  This is one of those times and it just kind of emerges out of nowhere.  Birdsong isn’t as good as the one from earlier in the week but Masterpiece is on point.  Might as Well almost seems expected after the Don’t Ease repeats.  

I remember being utterly unimpressed with Louie Louie and didn’t like the way this set was heading at that point.  Louie Louie is good though the arrangement isn't anything that's going to turn heads.  This was looking like a “third night” show with no big tunes.  Killer Sampson though.  Ship of Fools is fulfilling my picky deadhead prophesy but it too is solid.  I definitely did not appreciate the stand-alone Smokestack Lightning into drums, prob felt ripped off.  Rest of show is solid though; it really is a very good one. Jerry is clearly not 100% but he and the rest of the band are on despite the non-sparkly setlist.
